bank_df = read.csv('bank.csv', sep = ';', quote = '')
for (i in 1:ncol(bank_df)) {
  bank_df[[i]] = gsub('"','',bank_df[[i]])
}
bank_df = janitor::clean_names(bank_df)
colnames(bank_df) = gsub('x_','',colnames(bank_df))
bank_df = bank_df %>%
  mutate_at(c('age', 'balance', 'duration', 'campaign',
              'previous', 'day', 'pdays'), as.numeric)
bank_df = bank_df %>%
  mutate_at(c('job', 'marital', 'education', 'default',
              'housing', 'loan', 'contact', 'month', 
              'poutcome', 'y'), as.factor)

  testing()

#This variance inflation factor is to determine if any of the variables have autocorrelation. It appears that there is not enough autocorrelation to be concerned about, so no variables will be dropped on this basis.
model2 = update(model1,~.-age)
anova(model2,model1,test='Chi')
#The procedure I am using to eliminate variables is using anova tests to determine if any single variable has a significant impact on the test. If by removing the variable the anova shows there is no significant difference, I will eliminate the variable. If the anova test determines there is a significant difference, I will keep the variable. I am using this at a 95% confidence level.
model3 = update(model2,~.-job)
anova(model3,model2,test='Chi')

#After removing several variables, the model is only slightly improved, going from an AIC of 2259 to 2256.
test$yhat = predict(model16, test, type='response')

prediction = rep(0, dim(test)[1])
prediction[test$yhat > .5] = 1
test$y = gsub('yes','1',test$y)
test$y = gsub('no','0',test$y)
table(prediction, test$y)

#The prediction model leans towards false negatives-- that is, reporting a 'no' when the real answer is 'yes'. 
#I compared this model's performance with the original, unedited model, and it only got a single prediction correct over the original model. 
test$yhat2 = predict(model1, test, type='response')

prediction2 = rep(0, dim(test)[1])
prediction2[test$yhat2 > .5] = 1

table(prediction2, test$y)
